Good move, increasing the pressure the Black d-pawn holds on white's Queen-side.

White needs to loosen up the Queen-side by getting his knight in play.  Nd2 iis not desirable. dxc3+ loses the knight.  Bd2 would not have been helpful either.  With dxc3+ White's response will be followed with cxb2 and the rook falls anyway--just as with Bg3.  The best move is withdrawing the Bishop to its home square.
White can regain some of his lost material--but without a serious black error the game is lost.

Probably should have avoided the exchange with Qh3+, and follow that up with exd5.  White's queen would be badly placed, but some of the lost material would be recovered.  Pawn structure would also be weak with doubled d-pawns facing a connected phalanx of queen-side pawns.
